,Recommended,282400,17493602,"Posted: 11 August, 2015",all,Canadaball,"I decieded to remake this review, as the previous one was a bit disorganized.Wasting more than 1000 hours of my life on this game, I hope you can trust me with this review. That being said, welcome to Superpower 2. Superpower 2 is a ""geopolitical simulator"" sandbox game, you can design and build units, wage war, annex territories and entire nations, and a whole lot more. All in all, you play as the country you'd like.Now I can't stress this enough, this game is made in 2001. There will be broken things, but you can overcome them (more about that in a bit), and a word of advice, if the game doesn't work for you, don't write a damn negative review. Just because the game doesn't work for you doesn't mean it'll work for others.There is singleplayer and multiplayer. Singleplayer can be fun for a while, but the AI is incredibly stupid and doesn't do much, add to the fact that there are long-term bugs in the vanilla game, singleplayer gets really boring.Multiplayer is the GO TO place for this game. Or atleast, if you want to have real fun and challenges. Now, there are plenty of bad servers that go up through the day with abusive hosts, but there are also RP servers. RP as in roleplay. Now some are good, and some are bad. But assuming you know a thing or two about geopolitics, they can be a HELL lot of fun. Despite playing through hundreds of them, each experience is different. Some games don't last long and are really boring, whilist others are really intense.The drawback is that its really hard to get into, espicially since you do need some experience prior to getting into the servers that I'd personally recommend. As for the bugs in this game, the game CAN be modded and there are plenty of mods. This fixes the games bugs and can make the game way more fun. There's one for present day, cold war, WW2, and I'm working on WW1 right now.That being said, I can't really recommend this game for everyone, I was little when I first discovered this game and waited years for it to be greenlit, I do not regret buying this, I've made so many friends here. Nonetheless, if you're interested in geopolitics, and think you might be getting into some good stuff, by all means, buy it. It's not that expensive, either.The only real downsides I can say is that once you get used to it, the game is not very complex. And there are some ""bugs"" (i.e stackdropping) that mods cannot overcome. But these can be overlooked fairly easily."
