,Recommended,282400,11786083,"Posted: 19 August, 2014",all,"Jakeman, Noble Citizen of London","It should first be noted that this game is ten years old, but still manages to perform and satisfy excellently.Superpower 2 allows the player to take on the role of any nation that exists in 2001 (Yes, even Vatican City/The Holy See) and guide it on its path to become a world superpower. It styles itself as a geopolitical simulator, and that is exactly what it is, although it plays more like a grand strategy game akin to Europa Universalis IV or Hearts of Iron III or a mixture of every Paradox Interactive grand strategy game ever made (although it should be noted that one cannot simply assume the role of a dynasty or a character like in Crusader Kings II). It has a very fleshed out diplomacy, military, economic and politics system, and one can even create organisations like NATO or the UN through a treaty system. It is also possible for said treaties to collapse (In one game played hours before this review was written as Britain, NATO collapsed after America withdrew). The AI is very interesting and games are random (in the aforementioned game Pakistan ended up nuking India and invading, for example).The one problem I have with this game is that there is a constant runtime error crash as of a recent update (I believe), and I am hoping that said crash will be fixed or a workaround found. I also want to congratulate Nordic Games on getting this great game on Steam.All-in-all, I would recommend this game to anyone who has the money - it's an excellent purchase."
